A couple of pointers to help get you started:

Learn about the API

The API documentation provides all information necessary to make a request and to process a response. Code samples are provided per API operation in a variety of languages. Moreover, an interactive console allows making API calls directly from the developer portal without writing any code.

Feature your app in the app gallery

You can publish your application on our gallery for increased visibility to potential new users.

Stay in touch

Happy hacking,

The $OrganizationName API Team

properties.description:
The operation sendcsvevents adds a bulk list of events to the api via a POST 
A CSV file text is accepted with multiple events on the same file, with a correct header and separated by a  "/r/n" new line.

The csv formatted text accepted with "/r/n" indicates a newline between rows. The header row is always required and each string must be comma separated.

The accepted header values are:
bike_id, time, latitude, longitude, event_type, riderId, gender, age, resident

The events data should always match the header. Add empty commas to achieve this if some information is missing.

properties.description:
Operation to add a single event using the API via a Post.

To add an event there is a need to ensure that the body of the request is an Event item as outlined in the schema definition.

The definition of the event is the following:

required::object "bike_id","event_type","latitude","longitude","rider_info", "time".

Descriptions

string::bike_id: 3-letter org code + bike number

string::time: Timestamp when the event occurred (ISO8601 standard)

number::latitude:Latitude Coordinate

number::longitude: Longitude Coordinate,

string::event_type: Type of event being submitted. Value must be one of this two: "trip_start, trip_end, trip_in_progress, available, unavailable"

object::rider_info: Demographic information about the rider.  The rider_info array is required to exist, but all attributes are optional (see second example).  Note: if present, this data is only to be submitted on the trip_start event

The rider info is compòsed of the following child properties:
string::riderId: Identifier of the bike rider. No data standards imposed.
string::gender: Demographics, Gender of rider. Pattern: "\"M\" male, \"F\" female, \"U\" unknown, \"O\" other"
integer::age: Demographics, age of rider
integer::resident": Demographics, Seattle-area resident flag (0 = non-resident, 1 = resident, 2= other)

description: A representation of an event

Successful responses will return the MessageID for the event, which will be queued for SQL insertion immediately. If desired, this ID may be used to check message insertion status using the \"/statuscheck/\"
